Although the difficult mathmatical provemet and derivations of theries have large proportion in the lecture, Dr. Lin's tutorial is still quite practical for real machine learning development.
He noticed his audiences about many possibly dangerous scenarials while building an algorithm.
Like over simplification of original hypothesis set by arrogant human "wit", and the abuse of high complexity models which may cause overfitting.
It's very helpful to have these important concepts in mind befor I really start building my own algorithm.

Last week I installed and tested ArUco library on UbuntuMATE.
After that, I started trying to build my own AR system as the basis of human pose estimation.
I'll choose Eclipse as my IDE.
I think I will start getting overwhelmed by errors from now on.

This Saturaday I'll begin my last goal of driving practice this year, 
which is entering highway and get pass the Ba-Gua-Shan tunnel to Chaw-Tuen.
This will be the longest trip of this year.
I already checked the route and noted landmarks of important waypoint.
If I succeed in this test, the main goal of my driving practice this year will be achived. And I'll reduce the frequency of driving practice to onece per week.
